.TH wafrift 1  "wafrift 0.2.17" 
.SH NAME
wafrift \- WAF evasion toolkit — run without arguments for interactive mode
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBwafrift\fR [\fB\-q\fR|\fB\-\-quiet\fR] [\fB\-c\fR|\fB\-\-config\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] [\fB\-V\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR] [\fIsubcommands\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
WAF evasion toolkit — run without arguments for interactive mode.
.PP
Exit codes (CI\-friendly):
0  success
1  generic error (bad input, IO, etc.)
2  bench\-waf: zero bypasses on any case in \-\-evade mode
2  replay:    saved bypass got blocked (regression signal)
3  bench\-diff: regression vs baseline (see \-\-bypass\-drop\-pp)
4  bench\-waf \-\-validate\-only: corpus integrity errors
5  scan: aborted — target rate\-limited the probes (inconclusive, not \*(Aqno bypass\*(Aq)
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-q\fR, \fB\-\-quiet\fR
Suppress human\-readable output — emit only machine\-parseable results (JSON)
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB\-\-config\fR \fI<CONFIG>\fR
Path to a TOML config file. Default: `.wafrift.toml` in CWD or `~/.config/wafrift/config.toml`
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Print version
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
wafrift\-evade(1)
Transform a payload with evasion techniques
.TP
wafrift\-detect(1)
Identify a WAF from response metadata
.TP
wafrift\-probe(1)
Generate differential analysis probes
.TP
wafrift\-scan(1)
Fire evasion variants against a live target and report bypass results
.TP
wafrift\-bench\-waf(1)
Reproducible WAF benchmark: measure raw block rate AND wafrift bypass rate. Pass `\-\-evade` to actually run the evasion engine (off by default — without it, only the WAF\*(Aqs raw rejection rate is measured, no bypass claim is made)
.TP
wafrift\-bench\-diff(1)
Compare two `bench\-waf \-\-output` JSON blobs and gate on regression
.TP
wafrift\-origin\-hints(1)
DNS hints for `origin_bypass` (authorized targets only)
.TP
wafrift\-egress\-example(1)
Print JSON snippets for egress presets (e.g. Tor SOCKS)
.TP
wafrift\-techniques(1)
List or explain available technique selectors for `\-\-only`/`\-\-exclude`
.TP
wafrift\-completion(1)
Generate shell completions for bash, zsh, fish, or PowerShell
.TP
wafrift\-recon(1)
Origin discovery via crt.sh + DNS (authorized targets only)
.TP
wafrift\-discover(1)
Endpoint discovery: parse OpenAPI/Swagger, run GraphQL introspection, or fire differential parameter mining. Emits `DiscoveredEndpoint` JSON suitable for piping into `wafrift scan \-\-from\-discovery`
.TP
wafrift\-replay(1)
Replay a saved bypass against a target — proves reproducibility
.TP
wafrift\-report(1)
Generate a markdown findings report from the proxy gene bank
.TP
wafrift\-init(1)
Scaffold a `.wafrift.toml` config in the current directory
.TP
wafrift\-seed(1)
Pre\-load a gene\-bank with known\-working techniques (per\-WAF or per\-host)
.TP
wafrift\-import\-curl(1)
Take a curl invocation (e.g. from Burp\*(Aqs "Copy as cURL"), run scan against the parsed target
.TP
wafrift\-bank(1)
Manage gene\-banks: list / export / import
.TP
wafrift\-bypass\-probe(1)
Differential bypass scanner against a single protected URL. Fires 136 auth\-bypass header probes + path\-routing\-disagreement variants + HTTP method overrides; reports any probe that diverges from the baseline response. The Tsai\-class vuln finder
.TP
wafrift\-man(1)
Generate a troff man page for `wafrift` (and optionally subcommands)
.TP
wafrift\-audit(1)
Decompile a CRS\-class ruleset and report the holes an attacker can drive through it (the WAF X\-ray). Zero\-config; `\-\-ruleset` audits a custom Tier\-B config
.TP
wafrift\-harden(1)
Synthesize the minimal CRS\-grade rules that close the holes `audit` finds, prove zero benign false positives, and exit non\-zero unless closure is proven (usable as a CI gate)
.TP
wafrift\-legendary(1)
One\-shot demo command — runs detect + fingerprint + bypass\-probe (and optionally scan) against a single target, and stitches the results into one polished markdown writeup
.TP
wafrift\-listener(1)
Out\-of\-band callback receiver — pre\-mints unique tokens to embed in payloads (blind SQLi / stored XSS / blind SSRF / OOB command injection); logs any inbound HTTP request matching a minted token. The oracle for the vuln classes that never echo a verdict on the same response
.TP
wafrift\-parser\-diff(1)
Parser\-differential fingerprinter — fires URL\-shape variants that exercise known WAF↔origin parser disagreements (semicolon\-strip, backslash\-as\-separator, NUL truncation, double\-URL\-decode, fullwidth slash, dot\-segment, percent case, empty\-segment collapse, trailing dot). A divergence from baseline is evidence the WAF and the origin disagree on what the URL means — exploit the seam without any payload mutation
.TP
wafrift\-compress(1)
Wrap a request body in one or more `Content\-Encoding` layers (gzip / deflate / brotli / chain). The compression\-confusion attack: WAFs that inspect raw bytes pass over the encoded body while the origin decompresses normally. Brotli is the headline gap — many WAFs don\*(Aqt ship a brotli decompressor even though Chrome / nginx / Apache all do
.TP
wafrift\-smuggle(1)
HTTP request smuggling probes (CL.TE / TE.CL / TE.TE / CL.0 / dual\-CL / multi\-value\-CL). Subcommands: `detect` runs the SAFE timing\-differential probes that can\*(Aqt poison the connection pool; `probe` fires the exploit\-grade payloads (requires `\-\-unsafe`); `dry\-run` renders the raw wire bytes without sending anything; `list` enumerates the variants. Built on the same engine powering the `wafrift\-smuggling` library, but exposed as a first\-class CLI surface so pentesters don\*(Aqt need to roll their own runner
.TP
wafrift\-help(1)
Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)
.SH VERSION
v0.2.17
